ansactional significance to industries as well as a crucial locus of meaning and interactional participation for consumers. In addition to examining how industries connect books, DVDs, video games, lifestyle products, toys, and more to consumers, it also interrogates the changes in media circulation driven by the collision of digital platforms with existing retail institutions. By grappling with the contexts in which we buy media, Point of Sale uncovers the underlying tensions that define the contemporary culture industries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aMass mediaxEconomic aspects. 0aRetail trade. 0aSellingxMass media. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  aSale, media retail, popular culture, consumers, consumer culture, digital age, books, DVDs, video games, lifestyle products, toys, media circulation, digital platforms, retail institutions, contemporary culture industries, media.1 aAffuso, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnderson, Tim J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBak, Meredith A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBak, Meredith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrannon Donoghue, Courtney, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aComella, Lynn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElkins, Evan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHanna, Erin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerbert, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerbert, Daniel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJohnson, Derek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 a